<div style="padding:2rem;font-family:monospace;max-width:900px;margin:0 auto;color:#ccc">
  <h1 style="color:#fff;margin-bottom:0.25rem">Ember CSPT Lab</h1>
  <p style="color:#888;margin-bottom:1.5rem">Client-Side Path Traversal research lab — Ember 6 / route-recognizer 0.3.4</p>

  {{!-- Key Finding --}}
  <div style="padding:1rem;background:#111;border-radius:8px;margin-bottom:2rem;border:1px solid #333">
    <h3 style="margin:0 0 0.5rem;color:#f90">Key Finding: route-recognizer Decodes :param with decodeURIComponent</h3>
    <p style="margin:0;color:#ccc;line-height:1.7">
      <code>normalizePath()</code> decodes each segment, then re-encodes only <code>%</code> and <code>/</code>.
      Then <code>findHandler()</code> applies <code>decodeURIComponent()</code> again for <code>:param</code> segments.
      Result: <code>%2F</code> becomes <span style="color:#f44">/</span> — full traversal primitive.
      <br/>
      Star <code>*param</code> segments <span style="color:#4a4">skip</span> the final decode — <code>%2F</code> stays encoded.
      <br/>
      <strong>Double-encoding blocked:</strong> <code>%252f</code> → <code>%2f</code> (normalizePath decode) → <code>%252f</code> (% re-encoded back!) → <code>%2f</code> (findHandler). normalizePath's <code>%</code> re-encoding prevents the double-decode attack.
      <br/>
      Query params arrive <span style="color:#f44">decoded</span> by the browser's standard parsing.
      <br/>
      <code>window.location.hash</code> is <span style="color:#f44">never encoded</span> — literal <code>../</code> flows directly.
    </p>
  </div>

  {{!-- DANGEROUS SOURCES --}}
  <div style="padding:1rem;background:#1a0000;border-radius:8px;margin-bottom:2rem;border:1px solid #f44">
    <h2 style="margin:0 0 0.75rem;color:#f44">DANGEROUS SOURCES (decode %2F to /)</h2>
    <p style="color:#888;font-size:0.85rem;margin:0 0 0.75rem">
      These sources return decoded values — %2F becomes / before your code sees it.
    </p>
